70 (5) A financial model that allows the healthcare professional to serve all callers,
71 regardless of whether such callers make a copayment or have third-party insurance
72 coverage.
73 (e) The department shall, subject to the availability of funding, develop, implement, and
74 disseminate materials and training, including, but not limited to, the following:
75 (1) Training programs and curricula to be used in training hotline service staff to
76 recognize and respond to an emergency; to identify the appropriate state and local
77 programs, healthcare services, healthcare professionals, and resources for callers; and to
78 use any technology related to carrying out the provisions of subsection (c) of this Code
79 section;
80 (2) Promotional materials to be placed in conspicuous places throughout the state in clear
81 view of the public where similar notices are customarily posted; and
82 (3) A description of the hotline service to be placed on the department's website.
83 (f)(1) In addition to the general administration of the hotline service, funds appropriated
84 for the hotline service may be expended for the following purposes:
85 (A) Reimbursing healthcare professionals for healthcare services provided to callers
86 who do not have coverage under government or private policies;
87 (B) Developing and implementing training as provided in subsection (e) of this Code
88 section; and
89 (C) Developing and disseminating promotional materials as provided in subsection (e)
90 of this Code section.
91 (2) Funds appropriated for the hotline service shall not be used to reimburse any person
92 for copayments required by a commercial insurance policy.
93 (g) Any person or persons participating in making referrals to callers or connecting callers
94 with state and local programs, healthcare services, healthcare professionals, and other
95 resources pursuant to this Code section or participating in any judicial proceeding or any
96 other proceeding resulting from such referrals or connections shall in so doing be immune
